<HEADLINE>
A plea to remember we are one people
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Beach Runner &lt;LowHe...@gmail.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-08-08T08:20:00 </POSTDATE>
Few things are as important to me as my Jewish identify.  Jewish
thought, loyalty and
concepts are integral to my being and actions.

I saw a Jewish group on the web, and in spite of having being on the
web since the 80s.
Prior to web sites and browsers, soc.culture.jewish floored me with
the anti-Semitism.
But, here I had found a Jewish moderated group.  A group where there
would be respect.
After a while I found myself attacked generally without mercy.  OK, my
ideas were not
mainstream, but the attacks were often mean spirited and self
centered.  They were as
if they held the center of what is Judaism, and no other thoughts were
worthy.

When the concept of using a Rabbinical source, it turned out it had to
be the right
Rabinical source.  After numerous attempts at joining the community,
being subject
to personal attack, I left, while on occasion viewing the exchanges.

What I found was, it was not me.   The personal attacks, the
intolerance was rampant.
There was no joining together as Jews.   Moderators did little to
prevent the personal
attacks, and people did little to oppose mean spirited attacks.   So I
left.

It saddened me, for as Jews we must have unity.

Perhaps we need to reconsider that WE were slaves to Pharoh in Egypt,
and we
are the Jewish peoples. And we are to be a light onto the world.
Disagreement
is fine, and a great learning experience, personal attacks, mean
sprits hardly
contribute to unity.  It seems the only time we unit as when attacked
by those
that seek to destroy us.

Perhaps we all can reach into our hearts and be Jewish and support on
another.
Express how and why we feel differently, but not with hostility,
antagonism and a self
absorbed view that one alone hold THE truth?

I wish us all the best and when the time comes we can be civil and
respectful,
I would love to participate, learn and contribute here.

Bob
</POST>
