I'm not sure exactly whom you are referring to. I know there is a person
named Hillel123 (or something like that) who sometimes posts to the
unmoderated group. But I will say this, in a general way:  Generally
speaking, traditional Judaism tends not to be very liberal or open-minded.
Some people have an issue with that, and that is their prerogative. The
problem comes in when a person starts insisting that the traditional Jewish
view is in fact &quot;not Judaism&quot; and a secular liberal world view is &quot;Judaism&quot;
and anyone who disagrees or holds the traditional view is mean-spirited and
an antisemite. The reality is that there are very specific views which may
be described as &quot;Jewish&quot; views, and other views which are not Jewish views.
A person is entitled to hold whatever view he wants, but what he is not
entitled to do is to describe his personal secular view as being a &quot;Jewish&quot;
view when the Jewish view is just the opposite. Judaism is not whatever we
want it to be, and the views of the Reform rabbi from temple XYZ do not
carry the same intellectual weight as Rashi (and I have no doubt that the
rabbi himself would be the first to say so).
Best regards,
---Cindy S.
