That's all well and good, but the fact of the matter is not nor has there
even been one sole unified &quot;Jewish view.&quot; And that mythical unified Jewish
view is certainly not owned by a bunch of guys in Lakewood, or Baltimore,
or Williamsburg, or even Jerusalem.

For any given group of Jews that you might choose, you may well find a
consensus on certain issues. And divergence on others.

Just look at the differences between, say, Jacko and, I don't know,
whoever he argues with here. Can you categorize one as &quot;Jewish&quot; and other
other not? I don't think so.

There isn't even a single Jewish view on something as straightforward as
eating rice on Pesach, let alone more complex philosophical approaches to
life. As we've discussed previously here, I think you'll find that Micha's
&quot;Jewish view&quot; on certain issues diverges quite strongly from Moshe's, and
both of them are VERY distinct on certain issues from, I'd expect, Harry.

Which one is *the* Jewish view?

At the end of the day, if one Jew says it, then it's *a* Jewish view.
Beyond that, you need to qualify according to the group you're talking
about.

