Nobody ever said that there is one sole unified Jewish view, and I agree
that there is more than one Jewish view on a variety of topics, but there
are not an unlimited number of Jewish views, and just because someone cooks
something up in his mind does not make it a &quot;Jewish view.&quot; For example, the
positions that there is more than one God or no God at all are not Jewish
views. A Jew may eat pork, but that doesn't mean that there is a valid
Jewish position in which pork-eating is permitted. If you (the rhetorical
you) want to eat pork, that's your business, but if you come to SCJM and
proclaim that pork-eating is an alternate albeit perfectly valid *Jewish*
view, you are going to get an argument. If you decide the earth is flat, you
are entitled to your opinion, but if you come to SCJM and post the earth is
flat and that is a valid &quot;Jewish&quot; view and attempt to prove it by citing
pasukim (bible verses), you will get an argument. In the latter case, the
argument will not center on whether Judaism claims the earth is round or
flat but rather on the point that there is nothing particularly *Jewish*
about believing the earth is one shape versus another and that it's
intellectually dishonest to use the torah to promote your own personal point
of view.
