There is, or should be, one point of unity that we ought to all be
able to agree upon: Jews are members of a tribe!
Our biblical epics say so, that we are of the remaining tribe of
Judah, hence the name &quot;Jew.&quot;  Now, like any other tribe, such as
Navajo indians, for example, we have tribal law. They are the ancient
laws that the tribe members are supposed to adhere to, and are dealt
with by the shamans, or rabbis, who are presumably the students and
arbiters of the law for the rest of us.
However, just as most Navajo indians no longer believe in their old
tribal religion, there are many Jews who don't believe in the religion
of the tribe of Judah anymore either. They still want to belong to the
tribe, but they don't want to be browbeaten by the tribal shamans.
Nonetheless, there are some MINIMAL criteria for tribal membership:
your mother had to have been a Jew when you were born, OR, you were
accepted into the tribe by our orthodox shamans after an exhaustive
process meant to keep you out. If you passed their rigorous tests, you
are part of the tribe.
But there are many points of cultural interest that Jews might find
common interests in.Obviously, there is the religion itself. But for
those for whom religion no longer holds much appeal, there is a common
history, a common language, a homeland (zionism), a body of
literature, and other cultural commonalities.
In the 21st century -  a scientific century - religion alone will no
longer hold the tribe together. In the past, it had to. It was all we
had of  our own.That is no longer the case. We have our land. WE have
a body of literature and science and music and art and many other
things that Jews have been involved with for quite a while now. But
Jewish law, as well as lore, still has a role to play. it's still a
great body of literature incorporating a great deal of wisdom, and not
to be totally dismissed.. But being a Jew is a multidimensional
experience today, and shouldn't be narrowed down to a single vision of
how a Jew is supposed to be.
